Resume Repository Architecture Audit
Timestamp: 2026-06-09T155821Z
Repository: szmyty/resume
Scope: Repository architecture, publication pipeline, LaTeX structure, maintainability, resume organization, ATS compatibility, recruiter readability, profile readiness, documentation, workflows, artifact generation

================================================================================
1) Repository Summary
================================================================================
Purpose
- Specification-driven LaTeX resume publication system intended to support reusable sections and profile-targeted variants.

Architecture Overview
- Core entrypoint: resume.tex
- Style system: resume.sty
- Modular content sections: sections/*.tex
- Profile metadata: profiles/*.yaml
- Build orchestration: scripts/build.py + .latexmkrc
- CI pipeline: .github/workflows/build-resume.yml
- Output artifacts: outputs/resume.pdf and workflow artifact resume-pdf

Current Maturity Assessment
- [MED] Architecture scaffolding is clean and modular, but resume content remains mostly placeholder text.
- [MED] Profile definitions exist, but build pipeline does not yet materialize profile-specific outputs.
- [LOW] Documentation explains the intended architecture clearly and is consistent with repository layout.

================================================================================
2) Repository Structure
================================================================================
Reviewed
- sections/, profiles/, scripts/, specs/, assets/, outputs/, .github/workflows/

Findings
- [PASS] Separation of concerns is strong: content, style, profiles, and build logic are distinct.
- [PASS] outputs/ and assets/ retain directories via .gitkeep, keeping expected tree shape stable.
- [MED] No dedicated audits/ path existed before this audit; adding it is appropriate for operational traceability.
- [MED] No tests/ or validation scripts for profile schema or section completeness, reducing confidence as the system scales.
- [LOW] Single workflow file is sufficient for current scope but may become a bottleneck as variant matrix builds are introduced.

Scaling Concerns
- Lack of schema validation for profiles can allow silent drift between profile intent and generated documents.
- Single resume.tex orchestration model will not scale for many variant outputs without a generation layer.

================================================================================
3) Resume Architecture
================================================================================
Findings
- [PASS] Section modularity is good: each section is independently isolated in sections/.
- [MED] Section ordering is currently hardcoded in resume.tex instead of generated from profile YAML.
- [MED] Content and presentation separation is partially achieved: style is centralized, but content is still template-level placeholders.
- [MED] Profile strategy is defined declaratively, but publication workflow is not yet profile-aware.

Recommendations
- Implement profile-driven assembly (generate profile-specific .tex from YAML section order).
- Enforce profile schema checks before build.
- Add per-profile output naming convention (e.g., outputs/resume.<profile>.pdf).

================================================================================
4) ATS Compatibility
================================================================================
Findings
- [PASS] PDF metadata fields (title/author/subject) are present via \hypersetup.
- [MED] Current text content is placeholder-heavy, so keyword discoverability is not yet representative.
- [MED] Section names are ATS-friendly (Summary, Experience, Education, Skills, Publications).
- [LOW] Build uses modern font + T1 encoding; likely acceptable extraction characteristics, but no extraction verification is automated.
- [LOW] No ATS regression check currently validates machine-extracted text output.

Recommendations
- Add text extraction check in CI (e.g., pdftotext smoke assertions).
- Add required keyword checklist per profile to avoid missing role-critical terms.
- Expand metadata strategy (subject/keywords) for profile-targeted publications.

================================================================================
5) Recruiter Experience
================================================================================
Findings
- [MED] Current template is scan-friendly structurally but lacks real signal due to placeholder content.
- [HIGH] No quantified impact bullets or concrete outcomes are present in experience content.
- [MED] Positioning is neutral because summary and experience are not populated with differentiated narrative.
- [LOW] Visual readability baseline is strong (spacing, headings, concise sections).

Recommendations
- Replace placeholders with concise, metric-driven accomplishments.
- Prioritize top-third signal density (role scope, outcomes, core domain fit).
- Remove redundant generic phrasing once real content is added.

================================================================================
6) Career Narrative
================================================================================
Target Narrative Coverage Review
- MIT Lincoln Laboratory experience: [HIGH] Missing explicit narrative.
- Systems engineering: [HIGH] Missing explicit narrative and evidence.
- Platform engineering: [HIGH] Missing explicit narrative and concrete accomplishments.
- AI-native workflows: [HIGH] Missing explicit narrative and project examples.
- Publications/research: [MED] Section exists but contains placeholder only.
- Founder experience: [HIGH] Missing explicit narrative.

Narrative Gaps
- Current structure can carry these narratives, but content does not yet communicate them.
- No storyline arc across summary -> experience -> skills -> publications.

Recommendations
- Define core narrative pillars and map each pillar to 1-3 evidence bullets.
- Add section-level constraints for proof (metrics, scope, tooling, outcomes).
- Create profile-specific narrative emphasis rules in profile YAML.

================================================================================
7) Publication System
================================================================================
Findings
- [PASS] Build process is deterministic and uses latexmk with explicit flags.
- [PASS] CI uploads artifact and emits checksum summary.
- [MED] Local build requires latexmk; missing preflight dependency checks in build.py for clearer failure mode.
- [MED] Reproducibility checks (hash compare across environments) are not automated.
- [LOW] Documentation is clear for current single-artifact flow.

Recommendations
- Add build preflight to fail fast with actionable dependency messaging.
- Add optional profile matrix artifact generation in CI.
- Add artifact naming/versioning policy and retention rationale.

================================================================================
8) Technical Debt
================================================================================
[HIGH]
- Placeholder content across all primary sections blocks ATS/recruiter/career narrative quality.
  Action: Populate all sections with finalized, evidence-backed content.
- No implemented profile-targeted generation despite profile architecture being defined.
  Action: Introduce profile-aware assembly/build path and per-profile artifacts.

[MED]
- No schema validation for profile YAML.
  Action: Add schema validation script and CI check.
- No automated ATS extraction quality checks.
  Action: Add text extraction smoke test in CI.
- No content quality gates (placeholder detection).
  Action: Add CI lint rule to reject placeholder tokens.

[LOW]
- Missing explicit audits/ process documentation.
  Action: Add short docs section describing audit cadence and format.
- Workflow currently single-job/single-output.
  Action: Extend with variant matrix when profile build support exists.

[PASS]
- Repository modularity and separation of concerns.
- Build pipeline includes artifact upload and checksum summary.
- Core documentation aligns with current architecture.

[INFO]
- Current repository state is a strong scaffold for a production-grade system once content and variant automation are implemented.

